<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><channel><title>My notes</title><link>https://www.hungryfool.net/</link><description>Recent content on My notes</description><generator>Hugo -- 0.151.0</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 15 Dec 2025 17:44:20 +0800</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.hungryfool.net/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Docker Cache Mount - uv as an Example</title><link>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/docker-cache-mount---uv-as-an-example/</link><pubDate>Mon, 15 Dec 2025 17:44:20 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/docker-cache-mount---uv-as-an-example/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Docker’s &lt;a href="https://docs.docker.com/build/cache/optimize/#use-cache-mounts"&gt;cache mount&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;code&gt;--mount=type=cache&lt;/code&gt;) looks simple on the surface, but it hides an important mental model that often trips people up—especially when mixing &lt;strong&gt;root vs non-root users&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;different home directories&lt;/strong&gt;, or &lt;strong&gt;multi-stage builds&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This post explains &lt;strong&gt;how cache mounts actually work&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;why they don’t share by default&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;how to correctly share them&lt;/strong&gt;, using &lt;a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/concepts/cache/#cache-directory"&gt;&lt;code&gt;uv&lt;/code&gt; cache&lt;/a&gt; as a concrete example.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id="how-cache-mount-actually-works"&gt;How Cache Mount Actually Works&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consider this Dockerfile instruction:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"&gt;&lt;code class="language-dockerfile" data-lang="dockerfile"&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="color:#66d9ef"&gt;RUN&lt;/span&gt; --mount&lt;span style="color:#f92672"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;type&lt;span style="color:#f92672"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;cache,target&lt;span style="color:#f92672"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;/root/.cache/uv &lt;span style="color:#ae81ff"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style="color:#ae81ff"&gt;&lt;/span&gt; uv sync&lt;span style="color:#960050;background-color:#1e0010"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;When Docker executes this, it creates a &lt;strong&gt;named cache volume&lt;/strong&gt;. The cache is keyed by:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Agents Rising: Turning Intelligence into Action</title><link>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/agent-rising-turn-intelligence-into-action/</link><pubDate>Sat, 11 Oct 2025 11:58:44 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/agent-rising-turn-intelligence-into-action/</guid><description>AI workflow automation company n8n&amp;rsquo;s $180M series-c funding and OpenAI&amp;rsquo;s recent announcement of Agent Builder show that industry values the plumbing of intelligence as much as the intelligence itself.</description></item><item><title>Agent With MBTI Personality</title><link>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/agent-with-mbti-personality/</link><pubDate>Tue, 30 Sep 2025 17:53:33 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/agent-with-mbti-personality/</guid><description>Researchers found that enhancing AI agents with MBTI personality can enhance the way agents act and make them more suitable for tasks in various scenarios.</description></item><item><title>Hello World</title><link>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/helloworld/</link><pubDate>Tue, 06 Aug 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.hungryfool.net/posts/helloworld/</guid><description>Hello World, first post.</description></item></channel></rss>